Indonesia Stocks: Astra Agro Lestari, Indosiar, Medco Energi

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-03-04T05:06:08Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-04/indonesia-stocks-bumi-resources-indosiar-karya-medco-energi.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of the 11:30 a.m. Jakarta-time
break.  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  advanced 36.94 points, or 1.1
percent, to 3,531.48. The measure has gained 2.6 percent this
week.  PT Astra Agro Lestari (AALI IJ), Indonesia’s biggest listed
plantation company by market value, climbed 2 percent to 22,550
rupiah. Palm oil futures rose for a fourth day, gaining as much
as 1.3 percent to 3,647 ringgit ($1,204) a metric ton in  Kuala
Lumpur . Astra Agro plants only oil palm trees.  PT Bumi Resources (BUMI IJ), Indonesia’s largest coal
producer, gained 2.4 percent to 3,150 rupiah. The company’s unit,
PT Bumi Resources Minerals, obtained $143 million in dividends
from its stake in PT Newmont Nusa Tenggara and will use the
proceeds to repay debt, Kontan reported without saying where it
obtained the information. Bumi Minerals Finance Director Yuanita
Rohali couldn’t be reached when called at her office.  PT Indosiar Karya Media (IDKM IJ), an Indonesian multimedia
services company, fell 5.9 percent to 950 rupiah, set for the
sharpest drop since Jan. 17. PT Elang Mahkota Teknologi agreed
to buy a 27.24 percent stake in Indosiar for 900 rupiah a share.
The stock’s last closing price was at 1,010 rupiah on Feb. 21.  PT Medco Energi Internasional (MEDC IJ):  Indonesia ’s
biggest listed oil company, slipped 0.9 percent to 2,875 rupiah.
Medco had its share-price estimate lowered to 3,900 rupiah from
4,700 rupiah by Stevanus Juanda, an analyst at JPMorgan Chase &
Co., who cited the risk of delayed development of Medco’s Area
47 oil block in  Libya .  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
 bmoestafa@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at   dboey@bloomberg.net  